sharpe.tooltip:
Sharpe is the check of how smoothly the strategy earns relative to the full day-to-day noise in results.

What it checks:
1) whether the average daily result is positive;
2) whether that result swings too hard from day to day.

How to read it:
1) a higher Sharpe means the strategy gets more result per unit of total daily noise;
2) a low Sharpe means the profit path is too uneven or too small for that amount of fluctuation;
3) a negative Sharpe means the average daily result of the series is already below zero;
4) comparison is valid only inside the same historical slice.

Formula:
Sharpe = average daily return / standard deviation of daily returns * sqrt(252).

Example:
if two strategies end with similar [[total-pnl|TotalPnl%]], but one has Sharpe = 1.4 and the other Sharpe = 0.5, the first one reached that result through a much smoother path.

sortino.tooltip:
Sortino is the check of how well the strategy pays for bad days rather than for the whole day-to-day noise.

What it checks:
1) whether the average daily result is positive;
2) how painful the negative days are when the series goes below zero.

How to read it:
1) a higher Sortino means the strategy handles losing days better relative to its result;
2) if Sortino stands materially above [[sharpe-ratio|Sharpe]], the bad side of the series is lighter than the full daily noise suggests;
3) a low Sortino means negative days are too deep or too frequent for that level of result;
4) comparison is valid only inside the same historical slice.

Formula:
Sortino = average daily return / downside deviation * sqrt(252), where downside deviation is calculated only from negative daily results.

Example:
if two strategies finish with similar [[total-pnl|TotalPnl%]], but one goes through losing days much more gently, its Sortino will be higher.

calmar.tooltip:
Calmar is the check of how much annual growth the strategy gets per unit of its deepest capital drawdown.

What it checks:
1) whether the strategy can grow without falling into too deep a capital hole;
2) whether the final growth was bought through an overly painful worst drawdown.

How to read it:
1) a higher Calmar means the strategy reaches the result more cleanly relative to its worst drawdown;
2) a low Calmar means the growth was bought with too deep a capital drop;
3) the metric is especially useful when two strategies look similar by [[cagr-ratio|CAGR]] or [[total-pnl|TotalPnl%]], but very different by drawdown depth;
4) comparison is valid only inside the same historical slice.

Formula:
Calmar = [[cagr-ratio|CAGR]] / [[drawdown|MaxDD%]].

Example:
if one strategy has [[cagr-ratio|CAGR]] = 24% and [[drawdown|MaxDD%]] = 12%, while another has CAGR = 24% and MaxDD% = 40%, the first strategy will have the higher Calmar because it reaches the same growth through a much shallower drawdown.
